name: JG Bigfish
text:
I only give 5 Stars because I've been fishing there since 1976. If you don't know the River, don't take your boat upstream.
Props aren't cheap, I drive a jet boat. And still hit rocks. Beware.
Fishing has suffered from Stripers and Hybrids eating the Crappie. But if you want a nice stripe for the grill, It's fun when they bite. Bluegill and Shellcrackers are nice in summer on flies and ultra light.
Please read the rules and identify the Bass properly. Shoal Bass are a Protected Species on the Chattahoochee. Please don't eat them. The Spotted Bass are good and plentyful. Eat them.
Have Fun, be careful. Those rocks are slick and painful.
Watch your kids. Current can be dangerous and the water levels fluctuate about 4 feet, sometimes faster than others. Call the WP Dam generation schedule. Allow 2-3 hours for the water to make getting to the dam easier, but Never easy. Wear PFDs at All Times above the Riverview ramp in boats or kayak.
Also Please leave it cleaner than you found it. Its just the Right Thing to Do.
Yall already have nice pix. I may add my Eagle pix later.
Enjoy, but Respect.

name: Julie Thomaston
text: It's an awsome place to visit. But realize that if you don't know the river and how quickly it can change when the water rises your in a world of trouble. People not from here dont realize how rocky the bottom is and jump off the dam and injure themselmves or worse. We've had people to break their neck or die because they think they can do what the locals do. We know that the river is constantly changing. It, the river ,demands respect.

name: UFE Student
text: Highly recommended! Perry Lakes Park is a definite must-see if in Perry County! Located less than ten miles from Marion, it is a perfect activity to do before a delicious dinner while there. The park itself is huge with plenty of trails to walk on and benches to rest on. In addition, if one walks about ten minutes from the parking lot, Barton's Beach is also there which is beautiful to say the least. Here, a nice, sandy beach touches a peaceful river which is perfect for swimming, canoeing, or whatever else you could put your mind to. Overall, Perry Lakes Park is a must-see while in Marion, Alabama!

name: Gunars Cazers
text: Great place to camp, visit, not far from Tuscaloosa. We did a day trip here in the winter. The lake is beautiful. There is a spillway at one end where there are picnic tables and restroom - yes, outhouse style, but that's fine. We tried a little hike on the trail marked with blue diamond blazes. The tree markers are great, but no one has done any trail maintenance recently - hard to see where the trail is. There are swimming beaches on both sides of the lake, on one side, they look kind of abandoned. There were also camping sites on both sides of the lakes with fire pit/grills, camping tables, lantern posts. There were many hunting parties camping there. A friendly campsite host/ranger kept a close eye on all goings on in the park. Next time we will bring the canoe!

name: Crystal Payne
text: Really enjoyed our stay.  We finally found a park that had nothing wrong.   The sites are spacious and well thought out.   The restrooms are well maintained and there is lots to do. name: Jason Yeager (Jason)
text: This is a nice place to visit, but if you are visiting to fish, it may not be for you. The access to the water needs to be greatly improved, and fish attractors (such as fallen trees) need to be added along the shoreline in accessible areas. The grass is often high and if you don't spray yourself really well, you will be covered in ticks. I've never really had much luck fishing here so I make the much longer drive to the Bibb County Lake which is set up much nicer with better water access.

name: Wayne P
text: This is a nice, quiet park. There is a good bit of space between the back-in sites, and they are all relatively level and paved. The pull through sites are all gravel, close to the road, and somewhat rutted from the rain. The water and electric hookups looked new, or at least, very recently undated. The bathhouses looked updated, too. There was more construction going on in the area of the dock. There are two hiking trails (though we didn't take either due to the rain). The campground is heavily wooded. Now, that is  not a problem for at leasts our 38 foot motorhome, and we appreciate the shade on hot Alabama days. The down side is, if you have satellite TV you may have problems getting a clear shot at the sky. The biggest problem for us is, the only cell phone service that worked in the park was Verizon. Since we didn't have Verizon, we couldn't even use the phone, much less do email or surf the web. But, if you want to disconnect for a while, this could be a good place to do it.

text: Quiet, secluded camping spot on well maintained sites along the Alabama River. Good base for visiting Selma. If you're a fisherman, this is a great spot.

name: Agnes Arrington
text: I stayed in cabin #21 and it was so impressive! I wasn’t expecting to find such a clean, well kept place waiting for me, just like a motel room ~ everything provided from the time you open the door ~ I even had a screened in front porch, lol ~ it opened into a large living room/kitchen/dining area; then walk through hallway, immediately to your left was the largest bathroom with shower that I’ve ever seen; go down hallway to a very large bedroom ready for me to just relax and enjoy!! Did not have to worry about anything except bringing whatever food I wanted to eat, how marvelous is that?!  I also enjoyed nature at its finest, a walk around the campsite meeting new people, smell of clean air, hear sound of water in the lake and birds ~ to me it’s a place I intend to come to more often ~ plus, you can’t beat the staff who run the place, they make you feel special and really are helpful if/when you need it..I highly recommend Roland Cooper State Park! You’ll love it too!

name: Gypsy Soul
text: Truly a gem. Great primitive camping right on the Alabama river. Great fishing right from your camp. Mostly everyone ive met here is very nice and friendly and would give you the shirt off their back. Deer walk right through your campsite. They have chameleons. Gators in the area as well!

name: Diane Rhodes
text: This place is wonderful~! Beautiful state park with primitive camping, cabins, and RV hookups. The boat ramp and water is gorgeous! Plenty of restrooms, including showers. There's even a game cleaning station! You can purchase a bundle of firewood for $5 or four bundles for $18. The staff is amazing! We rented a two-bedroom cabin and it's kitchen is fully equipped with even pots and dishes. All we had to do is bring food, dish soap, and paper towels; the paper towels and dish soap can be purchased at the park store. Our beds were comfortable. The couch has a hide-a-bed as well. We love staying at state parks but we are genuinely impressed with Roland Cooper State Park!

text:
I was most impressed with the availability, helpfulness, and friendliness of the staff here. Some friends and I rented a cabin for a weekend get-together. The cabin decor is a little dated, however, everything worked and the beds were comfortable. DISHTV was available in our cabin. You must make your own bed with the linens provided. This is a new policy since the first of the year, they say to cut cost. Read the rules and there will be no other surprises. There are some basic necessities and firewood available at the office. We are planning to return for another visit.

Update: Made another visit with friends on the 2nd weekend of February 2020. Staff was friendly and helpful. This campground is well tended. Awesome experience!!

name: artsmonster
text: My wife and I tried to go primitive camping at Roland Cooper this past weekend. I am in a wheelchair and need oxygen constantly. So I chose to be secluded and brought a generator for my equipment and a fan. My wife is 71 yrs old. After the second day, in 90+ degrees heat and no shade we decided the rest of our 5 day vacation was either going to be in a cabin, or we were leaving. My wife went to the office to ask about a cabin. One was avail, so we booked that for the remaining 3 days. We asked since no one was in the camping area could we please take our time after sunset to remove our tent, cooking stove, etc. Laura in the office said no problem at all. In about 10 minutes Donnie pulls up in a golf cart. He said another man was coming in a truck. When he got there, they were going to pack our things for us and bring everything to the cabin. Paul arrived in 5 minutes, told us not to do anything but tell him how we want things done. He and Donnie took down our tent, packed our things, put our coolers and dry food in their truck. They drove our things to the cabin and brought everything in for us. In 90+ degree heat, and not even being asked. These people saved our vacation, and with me being in a wheelchair, and my wife's age, made our workload very easy. I wrote several reviews, and am writing you. We will be back, but when its cooler!!

text: My husband and I were able to visit Roland Cooper State Park for the first time for our 1 year wedding anniversary. Visiting another state and an unfamiliar campsite, we were both eager to see what the camp site had to offer. They had a very clean and accommodating primitive camping area (our camp site was next to the river). They also had a fire pit with a grill top at each camp site, which was very enjoyable to cook hotdogs, hamburgers, and smores on. We were also given the opportunity to rent either kayaks or a small boat with a motor -- we ended up renting the boat with a motor. We had one of the best times out on the water although we got rained out within the first 30 minutes of boating. Our little weekend was a beautiful and relaxing experience thanks to the accomodating staff and the park's features. Thanks Roland Cooper State Park!

name: Rob Collins
text: This little park was an oasis at UAB long before there was a Campus Green and other designed parklike spaces. I've appreciated this spot since the 1990s when the campus was less friendly to foot traffic than it has since become. Somehow this park is more restful and restorative than it has a right to be, located beside one of the city's busiest streets. If you find that there's an event going on here, slow down and pay attention to it. I've never regretted doing that.

name: Carson Elmore
text: You might not even notice this park driving past, but it really is a nice place. There are picnic tables available under a small grove of trees, several commemorative plaques and statues, and even a tree grown from a cutting from what is believed to have been the tree under which Hippocrates taught. I went in the late fall and it was a great little green oasis among the hustling crowds of UAB's campus. A great place to bring a book and relax, if you don't mind a little of Birmingham's traffic sounds in the background, muffled somewhat by the foliage. Check it out!

text: Definitely one of the best disc golf courses in Alabama, and the two tees, together with two baskets on most holes, make this course suitable for a wide range of skill levels. name: Sam H
text: Extremely long course, that is tiring just walking it. 21 holes. You start off on flat terrain, with some fun man made obstacles before ascending essentially a small mountain. From there you play in the woods along its crest before descending in a single shot down the other side. You then wrap back around to where you started with a few more open, quirky holes. Overall it is enjoyable for the variety of holes and distinct "sections" of the course. 3 types of disc golf in 1 course.

text: This place is awesome!  We had a birthday party here for an 8 year old girl and a 4 year old boy.  Emily was absolutely wonderful to work with. The kids had a blast and all the staff were great. We were really impressed with how clean and well kept everything was. We had a range of kids from 4-10 and there were a ton of things for all of them to do. They even put a safety harness on the smaller ones so that they could ride the larger zip lines too. I don’t think we could have picked a better place to host a party for our group. The kids were having so much fun that they didn’t want to leave. We will be back for sure!

name: Stephanie Casto Clark
text: We always love Hastings. Such a sweet, simple spot to bring my three young kids. There is a playground for bigger kids and a separate one for littles. A couple riding animals, swings, and toddler swings complete the play equipment. There is plenty of green space for playing tag, tossing a ball, or spreading out a picnic blanket. There is also a picnic table and a bench. There's no shade over the play equipment, but the bench and much of the green space is shaded also. There is very little traffic on the streets around the park. And best of all, we almost always see (and hear) at least one red-tailed hawk!

name: Marsha Graves
text: Holy Ground is a wonderful large day park (no camping). Open April 1st through Labor Day with a great boat ramp area that is open year long 24 hrs a day. Overlook area offers history of this area (see website) & is high up overlooking the Alabama river. Offers a terrific covered area that is great for weddings, restrooms, tables & grills, basketball court, large pavilion, nature trail through woods to ramp area. Lower park area is huge and offers a maintained & buoyed off beach area for swimming  on the creek, tables, grills, bathhouse with showers, 2 pavilions for rental, fishing dock on larger part of creek, birding area with tables & grills, nature path from beach around to river into bird area. Possibilities are endless hiking, biking, fishing, boating, swimming, family reunions, birthdays. Much to see & do here.

name: Cathy Lucas
text:
My husband and  I stayed here for 8 days during May and June 2021. Our reservations made well in advance. I have a few complaints.
1. Campsites were so close you could reach out and shake your neighbors hand.
2.  Cable lines had been installed, but someone forgot  to order the boxes.
3.  There was no WIFI really except at the front office.
4. Major renovations were going on during peak season which eliminated  one of the bathrooms and showers.
5. Although pet friendly, there was no dog park or place for our dog to use the bathroom  except for the  empty campsites.
6. For anyone with children,  there was no playground.
7. No pool
I hope with the major renovations ongoing most of my complaints  will be eliminated.
As a positive, the cleaning crew were amazing.

resp.text:
Hi Mrs. Lucas,
I believe you have us confused with another campground.  We don't offer cable or wifi, do not have any renovations going on, don't take reservations, and do have a playground.

name: Rod Moody
text: When I was 10 years old in 1951 we moved to Ridgecrest.... I am now 79...This park was there then.... All it had was some really nice swings and a Basketball net on the grass... There was a a softball area but it just appeared by us using that area as such...Not something really built by the city.. There was a shallow grass ditch that ran thru the middle and went out on Oak St. The grass was very nice and kept. However we never saw any city workers, ever. There was a couple of large bushes and a shade tree... We looked for 4 leaf clovers in the grass...There was actually 4 ways to enter the park....Bart Starr and family lived on National Ave. near that entrance....Everybody hung out in the park with their dogs and bicycles.....I got to ride my first motorcycle in the park...I was 13...Jerry Palmer let me ride his Harley 165... Gatewood Walden also rode his 165 to the park sometime. There was never any rules against anything and it all went great...no problems. Usually there would only be a handful of kids in the park.... No crowds...Never saw any grownups... Hope maybe some older folks comment on their early years in Ridgecrest,,,,I enjoyed my time living there... Rodney

text: We found this place last week in our quest to explore the area - we just moved here. It's a nice park with plenty to entertain the kids. There are two jungle gyms, a smaller one and a larger one, in the playground area, so all the kiddos have something to play on. Two swing sets, also, one of which has a couple baby swings. Right in the playground area sits a nice table and chairs under the shade trees - a gorgeous little spot, really. There's a pavilion with picnic tables, a grill, restrooms, and water fountains. A walking track encircles the park, and there's also a basketball court, a few baseball fields, a soccer field, and even a wonderful open field with a few small trees for picnics or other activities. This is a gem - we'll definitely be visiting often!

name: KJ Aubrey
text:
The owner was friendly over the phone at first, but I feel that she could have been more up front about the nature of her place. That would have saved us a wasted 23 mile trip both ways. Waterloo is a beautiful place, but I would rather stay on the free TVA land than at this so-called campground. The campground is actually a trailer park with some spots for camping. We stay in many campgrounds, some better than others, but this is the first time we have driven through a campground and left. I could not even find the camp office to begin with and everybody at the trailer park was staring us down when we drove through.

When I couldn't find the office, I called the owner back to tell her we had changed our minds. She did not answer her phone. I got a phone call later on from a different number and it was the owner. I let her know that her park was not what we expected and that we had changed our minds. She got an attitude with me and said, "Thanks for letting me know. I waited for you for over an hour." I then informed her that I had tried to call and she didn't answer. I did not bother to mention that she wasted an hour of my time and the gas that I used to drive to her disappointment of a trailer park that she is trying to pass off as a campground. If you do decide to camp in Waterloo, I would suggest that you turn right on the road before you cross the bridge into town and stay on the TVA land. It is well maintained, peaceful and it is free.

resp.text: I am sorry that our campground was not what you expected. Our property is 2 businesses, a small campground on the water with bathhouse, boat launch, fishing dock. The main portion are Lake lots that we lease yearly for vacation sites. It's not unusual for people to turn in the wrong drive; I keep meaning to get new signs but since my husband died in March I've been trying to juggle the whole thing alone. After we spoke, I did see that you had called the office number, which is supposed to be transferred to my cell phone. So I called you at 6:10 and we both missed each other. I apologize for my shortness, I have no excuse for that except that 14 hour days, 7 days a week sometimes gets me overwhelmed.   I'm usually pretty nice.  Our campground is usually not full in the fall, and the weather is perfect for camping. If you ever decide to reconsider camping with electric, water , and hot showers, I would be glad to make up to you your "wasted 23 mile round trip". Thank you for your review.

text: Great place for sunsets and sunrise over the TN river. And eagle watching !

name: Mary Morrison
text: Been going to this campground for 13 years....it is like family and going home. We camp at many different campgrounds from private to state parks and they all offer different amenities.  At Hart it is shaded, beautiful views of the water, hot showers and friendly people...the owner treats everyone like family...we love Harts

resp.text: You are family! Thank you!

name: RV Mobile Repair, LLC
text: A beautiful place to camp along the Tennessee River. Everyone seems really friendly there.  If you're there and you need some RV work call662 me306 at0937

resp.text: Thank You!

name: Lee Hemming
text: We were greeted by the very helpful and friendly owner. The views are beautiful, however with the description and great reviews, we expected a little more. This is more like a rustic fishing camp. It was recommended that we not use the coffee maker and the microwave at the same time. Yikes! 30 amp service is old. Picnic tables need help. Grass sites. Also there was a dog roaming in the park that was unfriendly, so we didn't feel comfortable having ours out and about. Paid $17 for the night, a fair price, probably. With a few upgrades, this could really be a hidden gem. Grocery and dining not close, so bring what you need.

resp.text: Thank you for staying with us, Mr. Hemming. Your review is pretty accurate, upgrading our electric and some cosmetic work on the tables etc have been in our plans. We actually met with the Utility Company last year , and are still waiting on their approval of the plans . The campground sites were built in the 1970's, and RV requirements have definitely changed since then. We do have some 50amp service, I'm sorry I did not show you those sites. I hope we will be able to get to work on that soon, and that when we do, you will come see us if you ever swing south again!

text: The good ole days of pulling up to the gate and paying to camp are over !! Now you have to contact recreaction.gov by phone or online to make reservations. If you make reservations and for some odd reason need to cancel let me warn you now ! I made reservations at 3 pm, found out at 3:50pm I had to work. I called at 4:20 pm to cancel. They ( recreaction.gov) told me a $10 charge will apply for not canceling within 60 minutes of my reservations.. So I said ok may I bump my camping trip for the following weekend ? I was told it would be $10 to move it to the next weekend !!! I'm sorry but $10 is $10 unnecessary dollars... the lady was rude and blamed the fee on bluff creek.. if I didnt like the Camp Ground host so much I would never stay here again. So be warned on cancellations. And one last thing- I was told to cancel it would take 14 days to get my refund less the 10 damn dollars !!!

text:
We only stayed here for 2 nights but we loved the campgrounds.
Everything is clean bathrooms included. The campsites are large and have big pads and table and room enough for big trailers.
We were right at the waters edge a very nice place to be.
There were also deer walking through the campground.
While in the area we went to Providence Canyon in Lumpkin GA.
The Canyon isn't far from Bluff Creek and is worth the ride bring your camera and walking shoes.
We will make planes to get back here soon.

name: Deborah White
text:
My famiy and I camp here at least 4 weeks during the summer. The staff are friendly, but abide by the rules. There is plenty of parking for visitors to your camp site. Each site allows you to have your canopy (for RV/Camper) open at all times. It also has a large pad with a picnic table, grill, and fire pit. The bathroom facilities are SUPER clean! In the womens restroom there are benches near the showers and two sinks (1 regular/1handicap). You have your choice of three bath facilities throughout the grounds. There is tons of nature all around. My husband takes his boat and spends the day fishing. There is a fish cleaning house when he returns. They have laundry facilities too.
Oure kids are able to ride their bikes without me worrying of them leaving the grounds. Its a nice place to relax and enjoy family time.

name: Bryant Betsill
text:
A Near Perfect little COE park on the Chattahoochee River in Alabama. Just 30 minutes south of Columbus, GA or Phenix, City (I didn't spell it wrong) Alabama Bluff Creek this weekend was very quiet. There were maybe 12 camp sites occupied of 83 available. Camp host and campers all said it was unusual for the second weekend after Memorial Day Weekend. If you use the COE website for reservations know that the camp map says sites have no access to the water / lake. Even if the map shows campsites up next to the water, understand that the campsite overlooks the lake and inlets, but from 6 to 8 feet directly above the campsite. For many campsites, you can see the water, but would have to have a rope ladder to access the water.
This is one of the smaller COE parks we know of on the Chattahoochee River. The property is well kept as are the bathhouses with laundry. This campground is very fisherman friendly with a screened in fish cleaning station and cleaning tables at every site. Most of the sites are separated by 30 feet of dense brush. Most sites are deeply shaded. (Ours was so shaded we needed the interior lights in the trailer at high noon.) Most sites are easy to back into. Only those along the Bluff Creek side have direct access to the water. There is only one thing that is a drawback, and that is the pulpwood mill adjacent to the park on the Mill Creek side. When we go back, and we will go back, we will camp on the Bluff Creek side and put a little more room between us and the pulp mill.

Disappointing by far. Visited with a small group earlier this month and was frustrated from the moment we parked. The man running the shop is clearly up charging for anything he can - $5 for a by standee to sit and “bubble watch”.

The rental shop itsself was a disaster from an organization, cleanliness and customer service standpoint. Thousands of dollars of expensive equipment thrown into the floor and in poor condition. I had the wonderful experience of using the restroom which clearly has never been cleaned. I knocked ants off of the toilet paper to use it. When I made a passing comment about the conditions of the shop and equipment, the man at the front desk stated “you don’t dive in the shop”.... doesn’t matter. This is still a representation of you and how you run your business!

When turning the overpriced and outdated equipment back in, the owner had the audacity to ask if we called the regs and if we didn’t, that they would have been damaged in the rinse process. I assume the only way his equipment stays somewhat in tact is if his customers provide care for it rather than himself. Pictures have been added to google for support. Needless to say, we won’t be back!

name: Sam Ogilvie
text: I took my initial training at dive land park great people with a passion for scuba diving. I did all of my certification dives there. Rental gear is available and is in good working order. The entry point is great, very easy access, you can drop off your equipment out of your car to the prep area about 20 feet and then it’s about 6 stairs down to the water. There are several platforms and a lot to see. There are concrete statues, beautiful large koi fish, massive boulders, aircraft all well within open water certification limits.  Water clarity is pretty good. It does get cold at 30 plus feet so bring a wetsuit and a hood. They have classes and trips for all summer.  They accept cash and PayPal.

name: Joshua Karnes
text: So we went there this weekend.  For those of you looking for it, I have a few tips.  If you use Google Maps, it will take you to this post-apocalyptic set of dilapidated town-houses.  (Seriously, Hollywood should film their next zombie flick there!). Just continue down on Northgate Drive until it dead ends.  If you look to your left, there is a car path through the grass.  Take that and then park by the creek.  There's a big water pipe that you can use as a bridge to cross into the "park."  This was our first time.  There was no trail per se, just a wide area that we could walk.  We walked it to the fence on the end and walked back.  I didn't see any marked hiking trails, but agree that this has HUGE potential.  Make sure you bring bug spray and clothes/shoes that you don't mind getting dirty.  Still though, our kids had lots of fun exploring.

My daughter’s young lab sliced his foot on a big chunk of glass. There was so much blood at first we didn't know what had happened. This is a place that could be so nice to take your dogs and family if the City of Hoover would come out and do a good cleaning! My husband contacted them and has gotten no reply.
Very disappointing.
**Please be careful to the right of marker # 12. That's where there is an abundance of glass.

Eagle Point Park is a well-kept, shaded park with 2 fenced areas for your dogs to run with no leash. There is a short running track and a longer running track.

name: Sam H
text:
Fun wooded course in a slightly sloped park. The terrain mostly plays as flat. Trees line every fairway and there are no open shots. It is not super dense foliage and there is usually an opportunity to save par on an errant drive if you get creative. There are a lot of short par 4s (around 425 feet) which creates birdie opportunities. A good player could probably eagle a few. Perhaps that’s why it’s called the eagle!  Unfortunately the baskets on holes 16 and 17 were missing on my round. The course wraps around a large dog park and there is a nice walking trail as well.

Overall this was a very enjoyable course. It’s not that difficult, but there is just the right amount of challenge to keep you engaged. There are no “signature holes” per say and a lot of the holes are similar in style. If you like to be challenged with tight line wooded shots in the 300-400 footed range, this is the course for you. A few easier holes under 300 feet will help your score

Whether it's events put on by the City of Andalusia (such as a part of Christmas in Candyland, Christmas Parade, and in conjunction with AHS, the Homecoming Parade), local schools (Andalusia Elementary School's Living History program, AHS's pep-rallies on the Court Square for playoffs), or local groups (countless amounts), the Court Square is a fantastic backdrop for any event in Andalusia. All the local businesses around the Square, and the spotlight WSFA brings with their tower cam on top of the Timmerman building, highlight just what Andalusia is.

That is a progressive town proud of what it comes from and embraces the ever changing future.

name: Mary Cook
text: First, let me say, we have been coming to Corinth to use the boat ramp for a long time. We love the ramp area. Plenty of room and it is maintained very well. However, we decided to give it a go and camp last night. This was a different experience. Our family was harassed and attacked by the campground attendants the entire 18 hours that we were there. The flyer says park on concrete or gravel and no more than 2 vehicles not including recreational vehicles. Well, my daughter parked in the gravel and we made sure she didn't protrude in the street but we received a notice saying she couldn't park there. We weren't even finished reading the notice when the attendant came flying through the campground on a golf cart yelling from the road that she couldn't park there. We repeatedly told the man that she is leaving. She was literally in the car and he was still telling us over and over that now we cannot park there and no more than 2 cars. My husband explained that we are aware and she is leaving. We had our other vehicle at the lake ramp all day and were simply swapping vehicles the the man couldn't understand this information. He was irrate and again, yelling from the road. The next morning we were leaving early because it was storming. My son pulled out ahead of us and pulled to the side to wait on us and the boat so he could follow us home. Immediately, the angry man came out again yelling at him that he cannot park where he was. He wasn't parked. He pulled over at the trash dumpster where we were otw to dump trash and leave. This man and his wife were horrible hosts. We didn't feel comfortable or at ease the entire day or night. We are clean and respectable people. My husband was a scout leader and highly aware of rules of the federal and state public lands. These gatekeepers ruined our evening and we will not risk returning here again for the mistreatment we received.

name: Trent Eubanks
text: Great campground for peace and quiet. Very nice sites with full hookups and good bath houses. Stayed during social distancing so camp station was closed, would have liked for that to have been operating like other campgrounds have done with their camp stores. Lots of trails but entrances are not marked well. Many trails need attention as does the boat launch area, otherwise would have easily rated 5 stars. Limited but usable cell signal, good enoufor streaming TV using WeBoost inside camper. LTE signal much of the time, 3G other times. Day use area and main boat launch is great, still need some maintenance. Will be coming back. Nearby Natural Bridge is a must see attraction with lots of moderate trails.

name: Jim Cornell
text:
This is a beautiful campground! The hosts, Deb and Ken in the Yellowhamer loop are the best! The campground is very clean and check-in was very efficient, which reflects on the host's hard work and attention to details.  The campground is quite and orderly.
Most sites are spacious and spread out from other sites. On line, it appears there are just a handful of sites available to reserve, but in reality, there are many more sites available as walk up sites. There are more back-in sites than pull thru sites, as well as a few primative tent sites. All the pull thru sites are located in the Yellowhamer loop. There is room for most big rigs.  The best part of this campground is there are full hook ups at all the sites, except the primitive tent sites. There are no water front sites and about 8 water view sites, the rest of the sites are forest view. Most sites are fairly level and partial shade to full shade. The trees along the roads are trimmed back.
There are 2 boat launches in the park. There is the "camper's boat launch " which is located between the Yellowhamer loop and the Firefly loop. This launch has enough room to launch 1 boat at a time, but no dock to load or unload passengers. The "public boat launch " is located about 1\2 a mile from the campground sites. This is a  2 boat launch with a nice new shiny dock to load and unload passengers.
Other reviewers have mentioned the remoteness of this location. These reviews are spot on. The closest store is about 15 mins away. Walmart is about 45 mins to an hour away too! Be prepared and plan meals accordingly.  There is a great marina/inn/restaurant only 5 miles away if you need a break from cooking and it also has the only bar for miles around!
There are only a couple of downsides to this place, but they can be dealt with with proper planning. #1 negative is TICKS! You HAVE to expect this, as this is a National Forest! SO, bring your DEET or other preferred repellant!  #2. The campground does not accept credit cards for walk-sites. Again, be prepared to use cash.
We have really enjoyed our stay here. What drew us to this remote, beautiful forest lake was the nationally-acclaimed clarity of the lake water. . . We were not disappointed!  We can't wait to come again in the warmer months when we can play in the water all day!

text:
Park has been let go.  Walking trail is fine, but the big pond is a total disaster.  Full of  algae choking out the fish and other animals.  Smell is awful, not to mention bad on the eyes.

Whoever is the caretaker or lack there of hasn't emptied the several gallon buckets provided as butt cans and they are full of water and algae and cigarette butts.  Also there is a large plastic PVC pipe just lying next to the trail, that's pretty.  Also looks as if someone throwed one pipe into the pond as well.  Dirt is washing into the pond and breaking away from the edge of the bank near the pump house.

You'd think the town of Springville would take better care of the people's investment but you'd be wrong in that assumption.

Guess the people need to take their park back from the city and keep it up through volunteers and donations.

Great scenery, multiple access to Tennessee river and streams. Dozens of paths and trails with nice mix of elevated and flat.

Quick respite or a relaxing day; you can't go wrong here.

text: Trail 201 was boring, nothing to see. We turned in 209 and the trail started to disappear. Then at the river it pointed for us to cross the Sipsey River, umm nope. name: Kurt McDonald
text:
Randolph Wild trail taken by itself is bit of a boring 4 mile hike. But at the end, you're rewarded with two really nice waterfalls. To reach them you have to know they're there. The first one is easiest to get to. After about 3.5 miles from the trailhead you'll start down a steep descent. The trail will level off briefly at a small campsite. Turn around and take a few steps back the way you came and you'll see a fork that you probably walked right by without noticing. Take that fork to the left. In less than 5 minutes you'll be at a very nice waterfall in the wet season (early to mid spring, or after a significant rainfall)

The second waterfall is much harder to get to, but worth the effort. Go back to the campsite and continue going the way you were originally going. The trail gets much steeper. Yes, I said much steeper...so be careful and watch your footing. You'll soon come to a trail crossing. Take a left and follow that for a couple minutes. You'll come to a small creek that feeds into the larger Sipsey river on your right. Turn left at that creek. There's a trail there that is well defined in spots, and hard to follow in other spots. Just keep going with that creek on your right. Keep going until you reach the waterfall

text: Clean and friendly park. So glad it's open again. Bring the family for a swing and fishing. Kid friendly with a great playground.

name: Chris Karr
text: My family and I have lived in the area for about 2 years now. This park is within minutes of our house. Great place to run, bike, picnic or my personal favorite, to fish. We have three boys, 9, 4, and a 7 month old. The two older ones love the playground here and we often bring our bicycles. Fiahing is great! I fish baitcasters and fly fish. I mostly fish for bass but there are other fresh water species. Overall, this a great place that fits our outdoor needs.

text: It’s ok but not nearly as cool as the Moss Rock Preserve in Hoover.  This one needs better maintaining.  On the playground, quite a few of the benches are infested with carpenter bees.  One of the see-saws has a broken handle.  Lots of litter and trash on the playground.  The coolest thing on the playground, the giant swing, is now gone.

text: Great place right off the highway. Creative offerings for kids. Not your typical playground!

name: Samantha Rice
text: What a fun free spot right off the main road in Owens Cross Roads! Our son loves the park and the walk around the pond! The pond walk has plaques with animals facts and a book to read as you walk. He enjoyed running sign to sign!

name: Brandy Wilkerson
text: Their Earth day event was great! Many vendors and local organizations there to show what was going on in the community with regard to environmental and social issues. Very interactive tables. Beautiful area for kids to play. Great trails and able to fish.

resp.text: Thanks for the 5-star review! So glad you came to Earth Day!  We are already planning next year's festival! It's going to be amazing!

They have a cute little pond that’s great for fishing as well and lots of trails and fields. The trail around the pond has interactive things for kids, like a story book that has a page posted every few feet, or animal trivia. It’s such a great place!

name: Darryl Gutierrez
text: This park is a hidden gem ! My kids aged 2 and 5 loved every minute. The playground is situated next to a small fishing pond. A family of geese was swimming in the pond when we pulled up. The playground was so unique and well thought out! It was mostly made of rustic wood and was an imaginative kids dream. There was a fort, a play house, a huge swing, a tunnel, rope bridge, seesaws, sandboxes, a music area, and tons of other equipment. My kids also loved the animals that were carved out of wood and scattered around the park. There are lots of great photo ops as well!

resp.text: Thanks for the 5-star review! So glad you enjoyed the many features! We have a few more to add and cannot wait for everyone to see and enjoy them!

It was the first of its type in the state and one of the largest Arbor Day Foundation certified playgrounds in the nation. resp.text: Thanks so much for the 5-star review!  Glad you enjoyed several of the areas of Hays Nature Preserve. Hope you visit often!

text: This is one of the best greenways we have been on to date, as far as scenery. There was a gorgeous deep river and a couple of big bridges to cross. I thought it was a little short, as far as greenways go, but we did not know it crossed over the road and connected to another greenway, so we are looking forward to that the next time. Great place to spend an hour or so, and I would love to see the other parts of it.

resp.text: Thanks for the 5-star review! Hope you visit Hays Nature Preserve again soon and explore more of the 538 acres.

name: Victoria Holdean
text: Kids love the playground area up front, and the paved path that crosses the river is nice. Haven't been in a while, but you need to plan accordingly if there has been a lot of rain as the path across the river floods over. If the river is really high, I'd keep to the main park side of the river.

resp.text: Thanks so much for the 5-star review! So glad the kids love the playground! It was the first of its type to be certified in Alabama and is one of the largest in the nation. There are many trails in the 538-acre Preserve. Good advice - when there has been a good bit of rain the trails near the front in the higher areas are the best bet for exploring. Hope you will visit again soon. Watch for the new programs and features on the playground we will add in 2019 - one is a story time/book and exploring club for kids.

name: Emmett Miller
text: Veterans Park does seem to be wheelchair-friendly.the bathrooms that were locked during a majority of the pandemic or now unlocked and there is at least one handicap that is  available. the floor on the men's handicap stall is almost always wet. There are two Pavilions in the park with picnic tables underneath them, sometimes the picnic tables are arranged to make it difficult to get a wheelchair through.  It is obvious that people tend to move around to make table Arrangements when they have a Party in the Park. The park is very clean and very well-groomed. the last time I was there there was a small sign inside of a plastic bag that said horses were not allowed. In three years of going to the park I have never seen anyone attempt to ride a horse in the park.

name: Mari C. Alexander
text: The Freedom Walk teaches/shows you so much about the history of the terrible things that happened in Birmingham and the fight to change the atrocities. I enjoyed the audio tour that we could call in and get further details on each stop. The reason for 4/5 is because of all the men (homeless or otherwise) that hang out there and congregate at one portion of the park or come up and try to give you an unsolicited tour (made it a little uncomfortable to view everything, and at our own pace), there doesn't seem to be any care given to the Reflection Pool and there's no water in it, and lastly because of the graffiti on the Pavilion.

name: Shir Carson
text: Educational, reflectional, and peaceful. Beautiful lawns and right across the street from the Civil Rights Institute, and 16th Street Baptist Church! Beautiful place to bring your children and or for peace of mind.

name: Dan Bird
text: Amazing and sad story of civil rights movement. I visited this place 4 days before Martin Luther King day with my coworker who wanted to explore his heritage.  I was a very appalled by the situations the marchers had to endure by local authorities.  If you wanna check out the real story check out the museum across the street from the church.

name: MrJcaston
text: What a powerful experience.  I love history and this is a site to see. I was truly moved and inspired to do better and ensure the freedom of the generations to come. The park is well kept and simply beautiful.

name: Sara Beth Wade
text:
This is a great experience! Especially as an add-on to the Civil Rights Museum. The museum isn't currently open, so I'm visiting what I can and the sculpture is well done and powerful in its own right.

I did get a little hustled though by a homeless man - he told me "those signs won't tell you anything, let me tell you everything" and launched into a barely understandable spiel that lasted for a few minutes. I didn't mind (and didn't feel threatened) but unless you want to part with some cash, you might want to tell him you don't have any up front.

name: Momof 3Kds
text:
We enjoyed all of the statues in this park. We could do the Civil Rights tour and the 16th street Baptist church was not opened due to covid. So this was a bit of a substitute.

There was a person blowing leaves and trash there "cleaning" so we had to scurry a bit because it was blowing on us. There were some people whom may have been homeless hanging out in the park so just br a little cautious and watchful there.

I would love to go back when everything is opened for a full tour.

text: Beautiful Historic Location, Everyone should Visit, Just WOW!! What Took place here in the early 60s is shocking..

name: Joey Prentiss
text:
Incredible place to learn about the civil rights movement. There is an interactive tour that is accessible by telephone. The stories and the sculptures are humbling. I didn't expect to feel as heavy as I felt. I also met Stanley who is in a wheelchair. Stanley offered to show me around. I found it best to walk in a clockwise direction.  I highly recommend visiting the park as the civil rights was not that long ago and it effects you whether you recognize it or not.

Note: both the civil rights museum and baseball museum are closed on Mondays.

We followed the Palm Sunday March, which MLKJ had also participated in when he got arrested and then sent the famous letter from Birmingham jail. That took us to city hall and Linn Park, with at least 15 signs guiding the way and sharing inspirational thoughts, photos, and history, as well as ideas for discussion and education for young and old.

name: Bevan Shores
text: Many walk by this park and don’t recognize they are walking on a historical site that changed the south. After touring the Human Rights Museum in Memphis, this brought to light much of what we learned there. The sculptures challenge you as you are able to see yourself in the perspective of those being horribly mistreated by racism. The dogs, the imprisonment, the water canons, the children killed by the church bombing. At the same site, you can see the march routes and follow those. Every 100 meters or so there is a marker with further information on what was going on at two key marches that took place. This isn’t something to be rushed through, allow yourself the time to experience what this place meant for history. Across the street from the park is 16th Street Baptist Church one of many churches bombed. After seeing the history of this site, it challenges you to think what your voice is about today...are there things that I need to be fighting for or speaking on behalf of??

name: Mist One
text: Visited this park on a whim. Made a two hour drive because of an episode of Malcolm Gladwell's Revisionist History podcast. The episode, Foot Soldier, is dedicated to a sculpture in the park. The park provoked a lot of thought and reflection about race in America and the evolving Civil rights movement. I recommend going during the day. I witnessed a man with mental illness become really agitated and aggressive when I was there. The police were able to de-escalate the situation and calm him down quickly, which was impressive - I didn't expect thing to go so smoothly. Hat's off to the officers who responded. That was the only drawback of the visit. We found a hotel without a reservation and enjoyed the night and next day in the city. Listen to the podcast and visit the park with someone you enjoy talking with. It's worth it.

Lovely park. I was immediately approached by a fella who I believe was homeless. He took me around and really gave me a good tour and told me things that I would not have known otherwise. He did expect to be paid for his services.  That would have been fine....but I was approached by 4 other gentlemen for money while I was trying to get back to my car.

Maybe the city could pay some of those guys to give tours. And discourage others from panhandling in the park.

name: linda smith
text: I find the horrific statues in this park highly disturbing and offensive. My children and I had NOTHING to do the the events of the past and I NOR my children/grandchildren should NOT be subject to looking at them... I will be checking in on acquiring a legal petition to have them removed !

name: Eve Edstrom
text:
My kids (aged 12 and 9) and I walked through and read each station.
We were all honestly taken up in the moment and very much enjoyed visiting the park

We paused for a long while to read about the four little girls killed in the 1963 bombing at the 16th Street Baptist Church...it was all a great stop to make in culmination of reading "The Watsons Go To Birmingham 1963" by Christopher Paul Curtis.

We did want to visit the Civil Rights' Institute but it was closed on the Monday we happened to be there.
